org.eclipse.keyple.core.seproxy.plugin.reader

Class AbstractLocalReader

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.eclipse.keyple.core.seproxy.plugin.reader.AbstractReader
      • org.eclipse.keyple.core.seproxy.plugin.reader.AbstractLocalReader
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ProxyReader, SeReader
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AbstractObservableLocalReader

    public abstract class AbstractLocalReader
extends AbstractReader
    A local reader. AbstractLocalReader implements the methods defined by the SeReader and ProxyReader interfaces for a local reader.
    It also defines a set of abstract methods to be implemented by the reader plugins in order to take into account the specific needs of the hardware.

      • isSePresent

        public boolean isSePresent()
        Check the presence of a SE

        This method is recommended for non-observable readers.

        When the card is not present the logical and physical channels status may be refreshed through a call to the processSeRemoved method.

        Returns:
        true if the SE is present
        Throws:
        KeypleReaderIOException - if the communication with the reader or the SE has failed

        This method must be implemented by the ProxyReader plugin (e.g. Pcsc reader plugin).

        This method is invoked by isSePresent.

        Returns:

        Throws:

      • getATR

        protected abstract byte[] getATR()
        This abstract method must be implemented by the derived class in order to provide the information retrieved when powering up the secure element.

        In contact mode, ATR data is the data returned by the Secure Element.

        In contactless mode, as the ATR is not provided by the secured element, it can vary from one plugin to another

        Returns:
        A byte array (must be not null).

      • isCurrentProtocol

        protected abstract boolean isCurrentProtocol(java.lang.String readerProtocolName)
        Tells if the current card communicates with the protocol provided as an argument.

        The protocol identification string must match one of the protocols supported by this reader.

        This method must be implemented by the plugin's reader, which is the only one able to determine if the provided protocol matches the current protocol.

        It returns true if the current protocol is the protocol provided as an argument, false if it is not.

        Parameters:
        readerProtocolName - A not empty string.
        Returns:
        True or false.
        Throws:
        KeypleReaderProtocolNotFoundException - if it is not possible to determine the protocol.
        Since:
        1.0

      • releaseChannel

        public void releaseChannel()
        Release the communication channel previously established with the SE.

        If the ProxyReader is not observable the logical and physical channels must be closed instantly.
        If the ProxyReader is observable, the closure of both channels must be the result of the completion of a removal sequence. TODO check how to make this conditional on the WAIT_FOR_SE_PROCESSING state.

        Since:
        1.0

      • transmitApdu

        protected abstract byte[] transmitApdu(byte[] apduIn)
        Transmits a single APDU and receives its response. Both are in the form of an array of bytes.

        This abstract method must be implemented by the ProxyReader plugin (e.g. Pcsc, Nfc).

        Caution: the implementation must handle the case where the SE response is 61xy and execute the appropriate get response command.

        Parameters:
        apduIn - byte buffer containing the ingoing data (should be not null).
        Returns:
        apduResponse byte buffer containing the outgoing data.
        Throws:
        KeypleReaderIOException - if the communication with the reader or the SE has failed
        Since:
        0.9

      • activateProtocol

        public final void activateProtocol(java.lang.String readerProtocolName,
                                   java.lang.String applicationProtocolName)
        Activates the provided card protocol and assigns it a name.
        • Activates the detection of cards using this protocol (if the plugin allows it).
        • Asks the plugin to take this protocol into account if a card using this protocol is identified during the selection phase.
        • Internally associates the two strings provided as arguments.
        • The #readerProtocolName argument is the name of the protocol among those supported by the reader.
        • The #applicationProtocolName is the name of the protocol to be the plugin when a card using this protocol is detected.
        Note: in the case where multiple protocols are activated, they will be checked in the selection process in the order in which they were activated. The most likely cases should therefore be activated first.
        Parameters:
        readerProtocolName - A not empty String.
        applicationProtocolName - A not empty String.
        Since:
        1.0

      • deactivateProtocol

        public final void deactivateProtocol(java.lang.String readerProtocolName)
        Deactivates the provided card protocol.
        • Inhibits the detection of cards using this protocol.
        • Ask the plugin to ignore this protocol if a card using this protocol is identified during the selection phase.
        Parameters:
        readerProtocolName - A not empty String.
        Since:
